rial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-47-working-on-the-train-of-the-mock-up-petticoat/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-47-working-on-the-train-of-the-mock-up-petticoat/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-08T19:08:33+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-08T19:08:33+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 47. Working on the Train of the Mock-Up Petticoat."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 47. Working on the Train of the Mock-Up Petticoat."><meta itemprop="description" content="In this tutorial, I want to show you how to make a mock-up train based on a standard petticoat."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 47. Working on the Train of the Mock-Up Petticoat.</h1><p><strong>In this tutorial, I want to show you how to make a mock-up train based on a standard petticoat. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p>When the style of the skirt implies a train of a rather complicated shape, it may be very difficult to form it using cushions and other supporting devices. I have an easier method for you.</p><p><strong>First of all, the inner skirt construction must be reinforced in order to stabilize the train and maintain the right balance of the skirt. </strong>A good solution for standard petticoats is to put two strips of knitted fabric between the side seams of the petticoat which will hug the client’s body tightly. After securing the petticoat in the vertical position this way, you can safely start working on the train.</p><p>And you can work on the train using the same methods we used for our mock-up skirt with a train.</p><p><strong>The only difference about making a mock-up train based on a standard petticoat </strong>is the fact that the plastic boning (for the mock-up) or steel wire (for the full-size garment) will start at the side seam, pass across the back, and stop at the opposite side seam.</p><p><strong>For this reason, I put bridges along the side seams of the standard petticoat. </strong>The plastic bones of the mock-up are safely secured by pegs. They hold their shape very well.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The key principles of working on the mock-up train remain the same. </strong>I secure the plastic bone at the specified level in the tunnel on the side bridge and then on the inclined and vertical bridges of the back, forming tunnels from the strips of snap tape, reach the opposite side seam, trim the bone, and secure it in the tunnel on the side bridge.</p><p><strong>The process of forming the half-hoop is shown in detail in the pictures below. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I continue installing half-hoops into the back of the skirt for the train until I reach the very bottom.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>There is very little left to do to bring the mock-up to the desired shape: </strong>lift the hoops where relevant shifting the tunnels along the bridges, pull up the bridges themselves, and achieve perfect symmetry to the central back seam.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The desired train shape can be achieved by adjusting the positions of the bridges. </strong>The pictures show how it affects the shape of the train.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Please look at the skirt balance. You can see that it is not perfect: the front of the skirt does rise up, although not very much, and the back is pulled down.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The best way to improve the skirt balance is to shift the side vertical bridge closer to the front and secure it in the desired position. </strong>Do not forget to stabilize the skirt by putting strips of dense knitted fabric along the side seams on the inside of the petticoat.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2047.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I suggest you put a piece of paper under the mock-up after finishing it and re-draw the floor projection with the train and with all bridge positions. </strong></p><p><strong>The train does not necessarily have to start from the waist. It may start below the waist (it will be more low-sloped then).</strong> In this case, the horizontal guide for the bridges should be sewn or pinned to the petticoat at the level of the beginning of the train. The bridges themselves will also start from this level and not from the waist.</p><p><strong>There are thousands of options when it comes to working on a mock-up train. I have only shared one of the many but I am sure you have got the general idea behind it!</strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3